metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #3921
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #129
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #113
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pewén, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the Wünelfe star, and the staggered cross Ngümin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

–

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

Patricio Isaías, September 2022

CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 License

metadata.name: The Binding String #8
metadata.description:
........._____.........
......./+_+_+_+\.......
..|.../+/.._..\+\...\/.
..\|.|+|..|x|..|+|..|..
.\/___\+\.|_|./+/__/_|.

100% code. Typography hand-made by @nathansonic

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Press s to save.
Click the screen to pause the animation.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

This piece explores the interplay of our concepts of communication and the web.

The transaction hash creates the randomization but it’s also the protagonist in this story. It dons the stone and halo as the key for how the blockchain speaks to you.

The transaction hash is brought purposefully into the piece in order to recognize its significance almost as a deity in the generative process. It’s the one thin string binding our real-life experience with blockchain.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

If you want a larger scene with more detail (larger resolution), zoom out using the browser zoom. Be careful as the more you zoom out the more ground elements will be created to fill the scene.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Pricing - Dutch auction
The pricing is a Dutch auction set at 4 - 3 - 3. 433 is the number of randomized variables in the piece.

Mint amount
The mint amount is 170. 170 is the number of unique elements multiplied by 10.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string started with a focus on maximizing the possible variations.

This has led to the project having 433 randomizable variables that tweak the scene to create insane variation. A lot of this variation is very subtle, but it’s there.

Random variables: 433 = 281 (rand int) + 62 (rand float) + 90 (Perlin noise).

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string has multiple layered scene elements. Some of these elements interact. Plants are forced back by the halo, elements closer to the central glowing rock reflect more light etc. There are 17 elements in total.

Here are some of the elements that characterize the narrative and aesthetic:
Stone circle
Planets
Plants (trees, bushes)
Fireflies
Animated halo
Glyph text
A smart, fully randomized custom palette creator.
Geometric shapes
Atmosphere scenarios ( day, evening, night, foggy)
Rocks
Mossy-ness
Crystal Geodes
Skewed hills
Ground elements (mud, grass)
Math based lighting
Galaxy lines
Shadow dust

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Extra special thanks to @nathansonic for his support, feedback, and code editions.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

3rd party code used:
Various bits by @nathansonic, including a custom palette creator.
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

metadata.name: Störungen #225
metadata.description:
Störungen is an exercise in suprematism in generative art. Not a new concept by any means, but (hopefully) uniquely applied.

In this work a single line is drawn from the center of the artwork, spiraling out and being perturbed by various constraints and disturbed by various controlling forces. These perturbations produce different illusions and, when combined, create feeling.

This piece is created in p5js, but is also intended to be plotted. Plotting will not allow for the blurring or color in the piece, but will instead give you a single color version of the perturbed spiral that you can print.

Open the token in a new window and:
- add &highres=true to the URL to get a highres image for printing
- add &svg=true to have the program create a plottable SVG
- double-click to download a PNG or SVG

metadata.name: Hayata! #11
metadata.description:
Hayata! emerged from my brief research on one-dimensional cellular automata (CA) and developed into a full project, since the resulting patterns were much more interesting than I had expected, especially when you mix the rules together.
Since the rules of this CA are so simple, they have something ancient, original and mysterious about them, like the I-Ching or other oracle methods. So I tried to give the CA a worthy frame by making the texture look aged and handmade.
I hope that your oracle only predicts good things for you :)
------
F.D. Berlin, October '22

Size: Between 1600px and 3200px both height and width.
Libraries used: chroma.js

metadata.name: Ailerons #85
metadata.description:
Ailerons, littering the factory floor, custom made and ready to be fitted to their respective aircraft. An accent trickles across the canvas, coloring any object in its path.

A study of light, built entirely in a 2d renderer, creating light and shadow with math and logic.

Press 's' to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js
